  {
    "key": "203-3a-teach-check-1",
    "title": "Lighting and Power Circuits",
    "objective": "Distinguish between lighting and high-power heating circuits.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In electrical installations, we categorize circuits by the type of load they serve. Lighting circuits are designed for low-current devices like lamps and LEDs. Because these loads are small, we typically use a radial layout protected by a 6A or 10A circuit breaker.",
      "Power and heating circuits serve heavy-duty appliances like electric showers, cookers, or immersion heaters. These are usually installed as dedicated radial circuits. A 'dedicated' circuit means it serves only one specific appliance. We do this because the high current required by a 9kW shower would trip the protective device if any other load were added to that same cable. Using a dedicated circuit ensures the heavy load has its own path and protection, preventing nuisance tripping of the breaker."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about why a high-power shower needs its own cable compared to a small LED bulb."
  },
  {
    "key": "203-3a-teach-check-2",
    "title": "Cable Types: SWA, MICC, and Thermoplastic",
    "objective": "Identify the properties and applications of SWA, MICC, and thermoplastic cables.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Different environments require different cable constructions. Thermoplastic cables, often called PVC (Polyvinyl Chloride), are standard for dry, indoor domestic use because they are flexible and cost-effective. For industrial areas or underground runs, we use SWA, which stands for Steel Wire Armoured.",
      "The 'Armoured' part of SWA refers to a layer of galvanized steel wires wrapped around the inner cores. This provides mechanical protection, meaning the cable can withstand being hit by a spade or crushed without damaging the conductors inside. For emergency systems like fire alarms, we use MICC, which stands for Mineral Insulated Copper Clad. MICC uses compressed magnesium oxide powder as an insulator instead of plastic. Because this powder is inorganic, it cannot burn, allowing the circuit to maintain integrity and keep working even in the middle of a fire."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on what the 'Armour' in SWA and the 'Mineral' in MICC actually do for the cable's survival."
  },
  {
    "key": "203-3a-teach-check-3",
    "title": "Ring and Radial Circuits",
    "objective": "Distinguish ring final circuits from radial circuits and explain how each operates.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "A Radial circuit is like a dead-end street; it starts at the distribution board, runs to each socket or point of use, and stops at the last one. If the cable breaks at the start, every point after the break loses power. A Ring Final Circuit is different because it forms a continuous loop.",
      "In a ring, the cable leaves the distribution board, connects to every socket, and then returns to the exact same terminals in the board. This creates two paths for the electricity to reach any single socket. The main advantage of a ring is that it can deliver more power using thinner, more flexible cables because the current is split between the two paths of the loop. Even if there is a single break in the ring, the sockets will usually stay live because power can still reach them from the other direction of the loop."
    ],
    "hint": "Consider the difference between a single line and a complete loop that returns to the start."
  },
  {
    "key": "203-3a-teach-check-4",
    "title": "Control, Data, and Alarm Circuits",
    "objective": "Identify the purpose of control, data, and alarm circuits.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Not all circuits deliver heavy power to appliances; some are designed for communication and safety. Control circuits are used to signal or switch other equipment. For example, a low-voltage thermostat in a hallway acts as a control circuit that tells a high-voltage boiler when to turn on.",
      "Data circuits, such as Ethernet or fiber optics, are used strictly for transmitting information between computers and servers. These require shielding to prevent electrical 'noise' from nearby power cables from corrupting the digital signals. Alarm and emergency circuits, including fire detection and emergency lighting, are designed for safety. These must remain functional during a crisis, which is why they often use fire-resistant cables like MICC to ensure they don't fail when they are needed most to protect life."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which circuits carry information versus which ones carry the power to do work."
  },
  {
    "key": "203-3a-teach-check-5",
    "title": "Wiring Systems by Environment",
    "objective": "Select suitable wiring systems for domestic, commercial, industrial, and hazardous environments.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "We select wiring systems based on the 'external influences' of the environment. In domestic homes, we mostly use flat thermoplastic cables hidden inside walls. In commercial offices, we often use Trunking. Trunking is a square or rectangular enclosure with a removable lid. The lid allows electricians to easily add or remove data and power cables as office layouts change.",
      "In industrial factories, we use Conduit, which is a solid tube (metal or plastic) that provides high impact protection for cables. For Hazardous environments, such as petrol stations or flour mills, there is a risk of explosion from flammable vapors or dust. In these areas, we must use specialized 'Ex' (Explosion-protected) rated equipment and sealed systems. This ensures that a spark inside a switch or junction box cannot escape and ignite the surrounding explosive atmosphere."
    ],
    "hint": "Match the protection level (like a removable lid or an explosion-proof seal) to the specific needs of the room."
  }
]

